  "slug": "porkolt",
  "title": "Pörkölt",
  "subtitle": "Hungarian paprika beef stew",
  "excerpt": "Beef chuck braised in vast quantities of sweet paprika with onion, garlic, and caraway until the sauce is thick, rust-red, and deeply spiced. Served with egg noodles and a spoon of soured cream.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pörkölt is the Hungarian stew most often confused with goulash outside Hungary. Authentic goulash (gulyás) is a soup; pörkölt is the thick stew. Documented in George Lang, The Cuisine of Hungary (1971) and Lesley Chamberlain, The Food and Cooking of Eastern Europe (1989). The key technique is toasting the paprika in fat before adding liquid.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The defining step in making pörkölt is adding the paprika to the hot fat after the onion has cooked and then pulling the pan off the heat. This is deliberate: paprika burns easily and turns bitter if it hits hot fat in an empty pan. By adding it off the heat (or at most over very low heat), you extract the colour and flavour without scorching it. The liquid goes in immediately after.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use genuine sweet Hungarian paprika, not the generic supermarket kind. The difference in flavour is significant. If you can get a mix of sweet and hot, the stew is better for it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
