      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the meat",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt the lard in a casserole over high heat. Brown the beef in batches until dark on all sides, do not crowd the pan. Transfer to a plate. Reduce the heat to medium.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the paprika base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the onion and a pinch of salt to the same pan and cook over medium heat for 15 minutes until soft and golden. Add the garlic, green pepper if using, and caraway seeds and cook for 2 minutes. Remove from the heat. Add the sweet paprika and hot paprika (if using) and stir into the onion, the residual heat will sizzle the paprika. Add the tomato purée and stir. Return to low heat and add the beef and stock immediately. Add the bay leaves and bring to a gentle simmer.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise until tender",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cover and cook over low heat for 1.5 to 2 hours, stirring occasionally, until the beef is completely tender and the sauce is thick. Add a splash of water if it reduces too much. Season and remove the bay leaves. Serve over egg noodles with a spoon of soured cream on top.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Always add paprika off or away from direct high heat; it should sizzle gently in the residual heat, not fry in hot fat",
              "cause": "Paprika was added to hot fat and burned",
              "symptom": "Paprika tastes bitter"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cook uncovered for the last 20 minutes to concentrate the sauce",
              "cause": "Not enough simmering time or lid kept on throughout",
              "symptom": "Sauce is watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce to the lowest possible simmer; beef chuck can take 2.5 hours at low heat to become tender",
              "cause": "Heat too high, tough beef needs low, steady heat",
              "symptom": "Beef is tough after 2 hours"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pörkölt is often misidentified outside Hungary as goulash. True Hungarian gulyás (goulash) is a soup, cooked with potatoes in a much larger amount of liquid. Pörkölt is a thick, dry stew. The distinction matters to Hungarians. Both use paprika in quantities that would alarm a French cook, and that is precisely the point.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
